## Bug Found

**File:** `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775461976032-9s27cq/src/utils.ts`

**Lines:** 5-11 (the `processItems` function)

### The Bug - Off-by-One Error

```typescript
export function processItems(items: string[]): string[] {
  const results: string[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++) {  // ← BUG IS HERE
    results.push(items[i].toUpperCase());
  }
  return results;
}
```

**The Problem:** Line 7 has the loop condition `i < items.length - 1` instead of `i < items.length`.

- When the array has 3 items (indices 0, 1, 2), the loop runs for `i < 2`, which means it only processes indices 0 and 1
- The last item at index 2 is never processed
- Similarly, for a single-item array `["test"]`, the loop condition is `i < 0`, so it never executes and returns an empty array

### Test Cases Showing the Expected Behavior

From `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775461976032-9s27cq/tests/utils.test.ts`:

```typescript
describe("processItems", () => {
  it("should process all items in the array", () => {
    expect(processItems(["hello", "world", "foo"])).toEqual([
      "HELLO",
      "WORLD",      // ← The last item should be processed
      "FOO",        // ← Currently skipped due to the bug
    ]);
  });

  it("should handle a single item", () => {
    expect(processItems(["test"])).toEqual(["TEST"]);  // ← Would fail: gets [] instead of ["TEST"]
  });

  it("should handle two items", () => {
    expect(processItems(["a", "b"])).toEqual(["A", "B"]);  // ← Would fail: gets ["A"] instead of ["A", "B"]
  });

  it("should return empty array for empty input", () => {
    expect(processItems([])).toEqual([]);  // ← This would pass
  });
});
```

### The `sum` Function (Working Correctly)

The `sum` function on lines 16-22 uses `for...of` loop which correctly iterates through all elements and does not have this bug.

---

**Summary:** The bug is a classic off-by-one error where the loop condition `i < items.length - 1` should be `i < items.length` to include the last element in the iteration.

